  "signature": "ed25519:9b4e1f72c3a05d8e6b2f94c10d73a58e2b1c6f4d9e07a3b5c8f2d1e4a7b0c93d",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA solver (Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2) operates under an ISO 9001-certified QMS with documented version control, regression test suite (>200 benchmark cases), and change-management procedures. Required Gradation 2 mandates at minimum a documented QMS with traceable version history.",
      "rationale": "The modeling team operates under DePuy Synthes and FDA internal QMS frameworks. Ansys solver version is locked at 2022 R2 for this study. All simulation scripts are version-controlled in Git with tagged releases. Regression benchmarks covering linear statics, contact, and large-deformation plasticity were executed and pass rates documented (100% for applicable cases). Achieved level 3 exceeds the required level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification at Gradation 2 requires demonstration that the solver correctly implements the mathematical model through at least one published benchmark or analytical solution comparison relevant to the physics of interest (structural contact, elasto-plasticity).",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical has been verified against NAFEMS benchmarks for linear and nonlinear structural problems. The team additionally reproduced the ASME PTC 60 contact patch benchmark and a Hertzian contact analytical solution to within 0.8% error. These results are documented in the project verification report (VVR-NC-001, Rev B)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires a formal mesh-convergence study with at least three mesh densities, reporting the Grid Convergence Index (GCI) or equivalent Richardson extrapolation metric for each QoI, with GCI < 5% on the production mesh.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted on the non-cannulated screw geometry: coarse (element edge ~0.8 mm), medium (0.4 mm), and fine (0.2 mm) in the screw-rod interface region. GCI values for stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm were 3.1%, 2.7%, and 4.2% respectively on the medium mesh selected for production runs. The production mesh contains approximately 1.4 million elements. Results are documented in VVR-NC-001, Appendix C."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 2 requires that iterative solver convergence criteria are documented and that force and displacement residuals are monitored to confirmed tolerances (force residual < 0.1% of applied load) for all load steps.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson iterations were run with force convergence criterion of 0.05% and displacement criterion of 0.1%. All 11 simulation cases converged without bisection failure. Maximum number of substeps was set to 1000 with automatic time-stepping enabled. No divergence events were recorded. Convergence history plots are archived in the project repository."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "A documented modeling protocol (SOP-FEA-NC-002) governs all analyst interactions with the model: boundary condition application, material assignment, contact definition, and post-processing. An independent analyst reviewed all model setups prior to submission runs. Peer review checklist is archived. The protocol was developed following ASME V&V 40 Appendix B guidance on analyst qualification. Achieved level 3 reflects the independent review step beyond the Gradation 2 requirement of a documented protocol alone. The required level of 2 was established by the risk assessment team based on the medium model influence rating; the rationale for this specific gradation threshold is described in the credibility assessment plan (CAP-NC-001, Section 4.2)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires justification of all constitutive model choices with supporting literature or preliminary experimental data, including contact formulation, friction model, and plasticity model, with sensitivity analysis demonstrating that alternative plausible model forms change QoI predictions by less than the acceptance tolerance.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V material behavior is modeled using a bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity law calibrated to ISO 5832-3 tensile coupon data (n=5 coupons, mean UTS 950 MPa, yield 880 MPa). Augmented Lagrangian contact with friction coefficient 0.2 (based on published tribology literature for Ti-Ti interfaces) was used at screw-rod interface. Sensitivity runs with friction coefficients of 0.15 and 0.30 changed stiffness QoI by <3%, within the 10% acceptance bound. Bonded contact was evaluated as an alternative and rejected as non-physical based on observed slip in bench testing."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires that all model inputs are derived from measurements or published sources with documented uncertainty, and that a parametric sensitivity analysis quantifies the influence of input uncertainty on each QoI.",
      "rationale": "Geometric inputs were derived from CMM measurements of five production screws (dimensional tolerance ±0.02 mm). Material inputs were sourced from ISO 5832-3 coupon testing. Torque preload on set screws was measured with a calibrated torque wrench (±2%). A one-at-a-time sensitivity analysis varied each input by ±1 standard deviation; stiffness QoI sensitivity to Young's modulus was 1.8%, to friction coefficient 2.9%, to preload torque 4.1%. Total combined uncertainty is within the 10% acceptance bound."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires N≥10 test specimens with documented traceability to production-representative manufacturing lots, including dimensional inspection and material certification records.",
      "rationale": "Eleven (N=11) non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories (FDA CDRH and DePuy Synthes internal). All constructs were assembled from production-representative components with full lot traceability. Dimensional inspection confirmed screws were within drawing tolerances. Material certifications (mill certificates) were obtained for all rod and screw lots. Inter-laboratory variability in stiffness measurements was 3.2% CV, demonstrating consistent test execution."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires that test conditions span the range of COU conditions, including at minimum two loading configurations or environmental conditions relevant to the intended use. Gradation 2 is accepted here because the COU is limited to the single ASTM F1717 standardized test configuration, and the regulatory submission does not require multi-configuration coverage for this device class.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 static compression-bending configuration at room temperature in ambient air. While the COU is specific to this standardized test protocol, only one test condition was employed. The required level of 3 was not achieved (achieved level 2) because no variation in loading angle, temperature, or simulated body fluid environment was included. This gap was identified and accepted by the credibility assessment team as a known limitation of the study scope; the ASTM F1717 protocol is the regulatory standard for this device class and multi-condition testing was outside the project scope."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "All model input parameters were matched to experimentally measured values: screw geometry from CMM, rod geometry from CMM, set-screw torque from torque wrench measurement, and material properties from coupon testing of the same material lot. A parameter equivalency table (Table 3 in VVR-NC-001) maps each model input to its experimental counterpart with documented traceability. No surrogate or assumed values were used. The required level of 2 was set based on medium model influence; Gradation 2 requires documented correspondence between model inputs and test conditions for primary QoI-influencing parameters. The achieved level of 3 reflects full traceability across all inputs, including secondary parameters."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires a quantitative comparison metric that accounts for both model prediction error and experimental uncertainty, such as the validation metric E/uval < 1.96 (95% confidence interval criterion), applied to each QoI.",
      "rationale": "The validation metric E/uval was computed for each of the three QoIs: stiffness (E/uval = 0.82), yield force (E/uval = 1.14), and force at 40 mm (E/uval = 1.31). All values are below the 1.96 threshold, indicating that model predictions are statistically consistent with experimental measurements at the 95% confidence level. Additionally, the percentage difference criterion (<10%) was satisfied for all QoIs (stiffness 4.2%, yield force 6.8%, force at 40 mm 7.3%). Comparison plots with experimental scatter bands are provided in VVR-NC-001, Section 6."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 2 requires documented justification that the selected QoIs are directly linked to the clinical or regulatory decision being supported, with explicit mapping from QoI to device performance specification.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are the primary outputs specified in ASTM F1717 and correspond directly to the performance specifications in the device design history file. Stiffness governs load transfer to the fusion segment; yield force defines the onset of permanent deformation; force at 40 mm is the ASTM-specified failure criterion. The QoI-to-decision mapping is documented in CAP-NC-001, Table 2. Achieved level 3 reflects additional sensitivity analysis confirming QoI sensitivity to clinically relevant design parameters."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 3 requires that the validation scenario matches the COU in geometry, loading, boundary conditions, and material state, with documented justification for any differences and demonstration that differences do not materially affect QoI predictions.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly replicates the COU: the same non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw geometry, the same ASTM F1717 test fixture and loading protocol, and the same material lot. The FEA model geometry was constructed from the same CAD files used for device manufacturing. No surrogate geometries or scaled models were used. The validation scenario is therefore considered directly relevant to the COU with no significant extrapolation required. The two-laboratory design provides additional confidence in the generalizability of the experimental reference data."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-dr-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The overall credibility assessment for COU1 is Accepted at Medium assurance level. Twelve of thirteen credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels. The single shortfall — Test conditions achieving Gradation 2 against a required Gradation 3 — was reviewed and accepted by the team because the COU is explicitly scoped to the ASTM F1717 standardized single-configuration test, and the regulatory pathway for this Class II device does not require multi-condition validation. All three QoIs satisfy both the percentage difference criterion (<10%) and the validation metric criterion (E/uval < 1.96). The model is considered sufficiently credible to support the intended regulatory submission.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
